{
  "text": "• Malignancies: Local paresthesia can be caused by a malignancy which puts pressure on adjacent nerves. For example a reported osteosarcoma in the left segment of the maxilla led to swelling and paresthesia in the left cheek [CITATION_1] , and periorbital paresthesia is usually a sign of malignancy [CITATION_2] . Multiple myeloma with extraosseous lesions may result in paresthesia of soft tissue [CITATION_3] . On the other hand the association between polyneuropathy and multiple myeloma as the result of various clinical variants should be considered (147). POEMS syndrome which is identified as Polyneuropathy, Organomegaly, Endocrinopathy, Monoclonal Gammopathy and Skin changes, presents with abdominal distension, progressive paresthesia and motor weakness of both lower extremities [CITATION_4] .",
